{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614299"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:43:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:43:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16356"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16356","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16356"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0,0.82,0.09,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9047"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64849"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9047","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9047"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16356"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50283"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4904"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"7198"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21514"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21517"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64849"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine neurological examination. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. You are reviewing the anatomy and function of her cranial nerves.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cranial nerves contains only sensory fibres?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Trigeminal nerve","Facial nerve","Vestibulocochlear nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Vagus nerve"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evestibulocochlear nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (cranial nerve VIII) is unique among these options as it is purely sensory, containing only afferent fibres. It has two components: the vestibular portion (balance and spatial orientation) and the cochlear portion (hearing).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etrigeminal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (CN V) is mixed, containing both sensory fibres (facial sensation, corneal reflex) and motor fibres (muscles of mastication).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efacial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (CN VII) is mixed, providing motor innervation to the muscles of facial expression and carrying sensory fibres for taste from the anterior two-thirds of the tongue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eglossopharyngeal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (CN IX) is mixed, with sensory components for taste and general sensation from the posterior third of the tongue, and motor fibres to the stylopharyngeus muscle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evagus nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (CN X) is mixed, providing parasympathetic innervation to thoracic and abdominal organs, motor innervation to the muscles of the soft palate, pharynx and larynx, and carrying sensory information from these regions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cranial nerve VIII (vestibulocochlear) is purely sensory, carrying only afferent fibres for hearing and balance.","Mixed cranial nerves contain both motor (efferent) and sensory (afferent) fibres.","The trigeminal, facial, glossopharyngeal and vagus nerves are all mixed, containing both sensory and motor components."],"references":["Sanders RD, Gillig PM. Cranial Nerve VIII: Hearing and Vestibular Functions. Psychiatry (Edgmont). 2010 Mar;7(3):17-22. PMID: 20436771; PMCID: PMC2861521.","Netter, F. H. (2015). Netter\u2019s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50283"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16356"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50283","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50283"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-24T18:50:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-24T18:51:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9047"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64849"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":n